          "body": "Three times the city *gate* appears (5:10, 12, 15) — the architectural space where elders sat to judge cases (cf. Ruth 4:1-11), witness contracts, and conduct civic life. Amos's indictment is precise: Israel's elite hate the one who reproves in the gate and abhor the integrity-speaker (5:10); they accept bribes and turn aside the poor in the gate (5:12); they impose heavy rent and exact tribute of grain from the poor (5:11). The verdict is the futility curse of Deuteronomy 28:30, 39: you built hewn-stone houses but will not live in them; you planted pleasant vineyards but will not drink their wine (5:11). The lavish architecture of Samaria — confirmed by archaeology (the so-called Samaria Ivories from this period) — is condemned by its foundation in extracted poverty. The chapter does not condemn wealth in the abstract; it condemns wealth that has used the gate as a tool of exploitation."
