          "title": "The Day of the LORD inverted (5:18-20)",
          "body": "Amos is the first canonical prophet to use the phrase *yom YHWH* (Day of the LORD), and he uses it to overturn his audience's expectation. Israelite popular theology assumed the Day would be when Yahweh vindicated His covenant people against the nations. Amos answers: 'For what purpose will the day of the LORD be to you? It will be darkness and not light' (5:18). The illustration in 5:19 is masterful — flee the lion, meet the bear; reach home and lean on the wall, the snake bites you. No escape is possible because the threat is not a creature but the LORD Himself passing through the midst of the land (5:17). The covenant election that Israel assumed was a shield turns out, when divorced from covenant ethics, to be an intensifier of judgment (cf. Amos 3:2 — 'You only have I chosen of all the families of the earth; therefore I will punish you')."
