          "body": "The chapter's most quoted oracle is also its most unsettling. God uses six verbs of rejection in three verses: I hate, I reject (5:21); I will not accept, I will not look at (5:22); take away, I will not listen (5:23). The objects are everything Israel got *right* — festivals, solemn assemblies, burnt offerings, grain offerings, peace offerings, songs, harps. Each item was prescribed by Torah. The problem is not heterodoxy of form but the absence of justice. Then 5:24 — the line Martin Luther King Jr. cited from the Lincoln Memorial steps: 'But let justice roll down like waters, and righteousness like an ever-flowing stream.' In arid Palestine, *nachal eitan* (ever-flowing stream) named the rare wadi that did not dry up in summer. God is not demanding justice as an episodic religious project; He is demanding it as a perennial water table beneath the whole society. Without that subterranean current, the visible cultus is noise (5:23) and stench (5:21)."
